1211E - Double Permutation Inc.
One can solve the problem with binary search by the length of a permutation. If the length is $$$len$$$ then:
just ignore all elements greater than $$$len$$$ (paint the with blue);
the expected number of unpainted elements is $$$2 \cdot len$$$: two $$$1$$$'s, two $$$2$$$'s and so on;
split the into two permutations with a greedy approach and check that they are equal.
If it is impossible to process any item above, it means that there is no solution with the length of a permutation that equals $$$len$$$.
There is an alternative solution without any binary search. You can greedily construct both permutations in order: add into them elements that equal $$$1$$$, add into them elements that equal $$$2$$$ and so on. Before the step $$$i$$$ you should check that there are exactly two occurrences of $$$i$$$ in the given array. After each step you should check that the current two permutations are equal. You can easily check it if you maintain them as ordered maps and each time you insert new elements at the same positions (the code below checks that next elements after the inserted are the same).
Here is the example of a solution in Kotlin:
import java.lang.StringBuilder
import java.util.*
fun main() {
val n = readLine()!!.toInt()
val a = readLine()!!.split(" ").map { it.toInt() }
val d = a.withIndex().groupBy { it.value }
val s = StringBuilder(n).apply { repeat(n) { append('B') } }
val pr = TreeMap<Int, Int>()
val pg = TreeMap<Int, Int>()
for (i in 1..n) {
val list = d[i] ?: break
if (list.size != 2) break
val rn = pr.insert(list[0])
val gn = pg.insert(list[1])
if (rn != gn) break
s[list[0].index] = 'R'
s[list[1].index] = 'G'
}
println(s)
}
private fun TreeMap<Int, Int>.insert(iv: IndexedValue<Int>): Int? {
val next = tailMap(iv.index).values.firstOrNull()
put(iv.index, iv.value)
return next
}
